The Trojan horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Funds will have to be allocated urgently.
Conditions will have to be imposed.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
The markets will calm down.
The long-term consequences will not be prohibitive, but there will be problems ahead.
Some will say that the fatal error was allowing Greece to adopt the euro first.
It was already evident that the country was not ready.
Its fiscal policy was already out of control when it joined the monetary union in 2001, and its trade unions were already pressuring for Greek wages to align with those in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as a mirror of its own future.
And if not, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy are doing slightly better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face significant budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to boost exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to seek assistance.
All of this raises a single question: was the real mistake not in creating the euro?
In the sense that I was one of the few Americans to encourage the idea of a European currency, you would be justified in asking: are you reconsidering your initial position?
My answer is no, creating the euro was not an error, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway along the path to a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis could well make this one look like a walk in the park.
If it wants to complete its monetary union, Europe will have to create its own emergency financing mechanism.
Today, the members of the Union can offer their aid to Greece only by circumventing the regulations that prevent them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond the control of a country.
This exacerbates the uncertainty.
When European leaders provide assistance, public opinion and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems result from the Treaty of Lisbon, then it must be amended.
In addition, the aid should not be granted solely under certain conditions, but should be accompanied by a temporary control of the national budget by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
History shows that simple promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, the countries subjected to such measures will express their indignation.
But no one is forcing them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Note that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
One could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily handed over its budget to an expert specifically appointed by President Barack Obama's administration?
In fact, it would not bother them too much.
The expert would not be a native Californian, but American.
The public would understand that he would act in the interest of the Californian state as well as the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from whom these orders would emanate, would reassure them.
The Europeans do not do things like this because they first and foremost see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereignty prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant due to its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties but also closer political ties.
Those who have a solid emergency aid mechanism will really have to account for it.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of bailout because they know well who will be responsible for it.
The Germans oppose anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany also has a share of responsibility in this crisis.
She wanted an incredibly independent central bank that was not obliged to account but which today has adopted an overly accommodative monetary policy, thereby critically worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
The huge current surpluses of Germany exacerbate their situation.
In addition, its fiscal stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has consequently benefited from the creation of the euro.
She should do the same.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency lending facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
She must provide more fiscal support.
Isn't she best positioned to push for a more accountable European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that will lead Europe towards a more mature political integration.
One can only hope.
